Telegem - Framework Reference (Senior Developer Edition)

🏗️ ARCHITECTURE & DESIGN PHILOSOPHY

Core Paradigms

1). Async-First Architecture

· Built on async/await patterns via httpx gem
· Non-blocking I/O throughout the stack
· No thread pool limitations (vs traditional thread-per-request)
· Fiber-based concurrency with true cooperative scheduling

2). Telegraf.js Inspiration

· Familiar DSL for JavaScript developers migrating to Ruby
· Middleware pipeline as first-class citizen
· Context (ctx) object as primary API surface
· Scene system for stateful conversations

3). Modular, Extensible Design

· Pluggable session stores (Memory, Redis, custom)
· Composable middleware chain
· Loose coupling between components
· Convention over configuration where sensible

📦 CORE COMPONENTS

1. Bot Class (Telegem.new)

```ruby
# Initialization with all options
bot = Telegem.new(token, 
  logger: custom_logger,           # Logger instance
  session_store: redis_store,      # Session::Base store
  timeout: 30,                     # API timeout seconds
  pool_size: 10,                   # Async pool size
  middleware: [AuthMiddleware.new] # Pre-registered middleware
)
```

2. Handler System (Three Types)

```ruby
# Type 1: Command Handlers (explicit /commands)
bot.command('start', 'help', 'settings') do |ctx|
  ctx.reply("Command received")
end

# Type 2: Pattern Handlers (regex/text matching)
bot.hears(/hello|hi|hey/i) do |ctx|
  ctx.reply("Greeting detected")
end

bot.hears("help") do |ctx|  # Exact string match
  ctx.reply("Help triggered")
end

# Type 3: Generic Handlers (type-based routing)
bot.on(:message) { |ctx| }          # All messages
bot.on(:callback_query) { |ctx| }   # Button clicks
bot.on(:inline_query) { |ctx| }     # Inline mode queries
bot.on(:chat_member) { |ctx| }      # Member updates
```

3. Context (ctx) Object - Complete Surface API

Properties (read-only):

```ruby
ctx.update           # Raw Update object
ctx.message          # Message or nil
ctx.callback_query   # CallbackQuery or nil  
ctx.inline_query     # InlineQuery or nil
ctx.from             # User who triggered update
ctx.chat             # Chat where update occurred
ctx.user_id          # ctx.from.id shortcut
ctx.chat_id          # ctx.chat.id shortcut
ctx.data             # Callback data (if callback_query)
ctx.query            # Inline query text (if inline_query)
ctx.match            # Regex match data from hears()
ctx.session          # User session Hash (persistent)
ctx.state            # Request state Hash (ephemeral)
```

Methods (by category):

```ruby
# Messaging (30+ methods)
ctx.reply(text, **options)          # Primary send method
ctx.edit_message_text(text, **options)
ctx.delete_message(message_id = nil)
ctx.forward_message(from_chat_id, message_id)
ctx.copy_message(from_chat_id, message_id)

# Media (15 methods)
ctx.photo(file, caption: nil, **options)
ctx.video(file, caption: nil, **options)
ctx.document(file, caption: nil, **options)
ctx.audio(file, caption: nil, **options)
ctx.voice(file, caption: nil, **options)
ctx.sticker(file, **options)

# Chat Actions (10 methods)
ctx.typing(**options)
ctx.uploading_photo(**options)
ctx.uploading_video(**options)
ctx.with_typing { long_operation }

# Chat Management (25+ methods)
ctx.get_chat(**options)
ctx.get_chat_administrators(**options)
ctx.pin_message(message_id, **options)
ctx.kick_chat_member(user_id, **options)
ctx.ban_chat_member(user_id, **options)
ctx.set_chat_title(title, **options)

# Callback/Inline (8 methods)
ctx.answer_callback_query(text: nil, **options)
ctx.answer_inline_query(results, **options)
ctx.edit_message_reply_markup(reply_markup, **options)

# Scene Management (4 methods)
ctx.enter_scene(scene_name, **options)
ctx.leave_scene(**options)
ctx.current_scene
```

4. Middleware Pipeline

```ruby
# Registration (three styles)
bot.use(AuthenticationMiddleware.new)  # Class instance
bot.use { |ctx, next| ... }           # Block
bot.use(middleware_class, *args)      # Class with args

# Execution order: FIFO (first registered, first executed)
# Chain termination: Return early without calling next.call(ctx)

# Built-in middleware:
# - Session::Middleware (auto-loads/saves session)
# - Error handling middleware
# - Logging middleware
```

5. Scene System (Stateful Conversations)

```ruby
# Definition
bot.scene(:onboarding) do
  # Hooks
  on_enter { |ctx| ctx.reply("Welcome!") }
  on_leave { |ctx| ctx.reply("Goodbye!") }
  
  # Steps (stateful progression)
  step :ask_name do |ctx|
    ctx.reply("What's your name?")
    # Store in session for later steps
    ctx.session[:current_step] = :ask_name
  end
  
  step :ask_email do |ctx|
    # Previous step's answer available in ctx.message.text
    ctx.session[:name] = ctx.message.text
    ctx.reply("Hi #{ctx.session[:name]}! What's your email?")
  end
  
  step :complete do |ctx|
    ctx.session[:email] = ctx.message.text
    ctx.reply("Registration complete!")
    ctx.leave_scene
  end
end

# Navigation
ctx.enter_scene(:onboarding)                 # Start at first step
ctx.enter_scene(:onboarding, step: :ask_email) # Start at specific step
ctx.leave_scene                              # Exit scene
ctx.current_scene.process_step(ctx, :ask_name) # Manual step control
```

6. Session Management

```ruby
# Storage backends (pluggable)
memory_store = Telegem::Session::MemoryStore.new
redis_store = Telegem::Session::RedisStore.new(Redis.new)

# API (consistent across backends)
store.set(user_id, data, ttl: 3600)  # Set with TTL
store.get(user_id)                   # Get data
store.exist?(user_id)                # Check existence
store.delete(user_id)                # Delete data
store.keys                           # List all keys
store.scan("pattern*", count: 10)    # Pattern search
store.ttl(user_id)                   # Get remaining TTL

# Auto-managed via Session::Middleware
# ctx.session is automatically persisted
```

7. Keyboard Builders (Fluent DSL)

```ruby
# Reply Keyboard (persists in chat)
keyboard = Telegem::Markup.keyboard do
  row "Button 1", "Button 2"
  row do
    button "Contact", request_contact: true
    button "Location", request_location: true
  end
  row { button "Poll", request_poll: { type: "quiz" } }
end.resize.one_time.selective

# Inline Keyboard (message-embedded)
inline = Telegem::Markup.inline do
  row do
    button "Option A", callback_data: "opt_a"
    button "Option B", callback_data: "opt_b"
  end
  row do
    button "Open URL", url: "https://example.com"
    button "Switch Inline", switch_inline_query: "query"
    button "Pay", pay: true
  end
end

# Usage
ctx.reply("Choose:", reply_markup: keyboard)
ctx.reply("Select:", reply_markup: inline)
```

⚡ PERFORMANCE CHARACTERISTICS

Concurrency Model

```
Traditional (telegram-bot-ruby):
  Request → Thread Pool (limited) → Blocking HTTP → Response
  │
  ├── Thread contention under load
  ├── Memory overhead per thread (~1MB)
  └── Context switching overhead

Telegem (async/await):
  Request → Fiber (lightweight) → Async HTTP → Response
  │
  ├── Thousands of concurrent fibers
  ├── ~4KB memory per fiber
  └── Cooperative scheduling (no OS context switches)
```

Benchmark Considerations

```ruby
# Async advantages:
# - Higher throughput under concurrent load
# - Better memory efficiency
# - Lower latency for I/O-bound operations

# Sync advantages:
# - Simpler debugging/tracing
# - Better CPU-bound performance (no fiber scheduling)
# - More predictable under very low load
```

🚀 PRODUCTION DEPLOYMENT

Deployment Modes

```ruby
# 1. Polling (Development/Simple)
bot.start_polling(timeout: 30, limit: 100)

# 2. Webhook (Production)
# a) Built-in server
server = bot.webhook_server(
  port: ENV['PORT'] || 3000,
  host: '0.0.0.0',
  endpoint: Async::HTTP::Endpoint.parse("https://#{ENV['DOMAIN']}")
)

# b) Rack middleware (mount in existing app)
use Telegem::Webhook::Middleware, bot, secret_token: ENV['SECRET']

# c) Standalone with Puma
# config/puma.rb
workers ENV['WEB_CONCURRENCY'] || 2
threads_count = ENV['RAILS_MAX_THREADS'] || 5
threads threads_count, threads_count
```

